WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.880
Good morning and welcome to PositConf 2025.

00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:15.200
Hopefully my slides will show up momentarily.

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:16.200
So my name is Hadley Wickham.

00:00:16.200 --> 00:00:21.200
It's my great pleasure to welcome you to PositConf here in Atlanta.

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:27.799
And my job is just to take a couple of minutes to help you be as successful as possible with

00:00:27.799 --> 00:00:29.879
conf so you have a great time.

00:00:29.879 --> 00:00:33.160
To that end, the first point I want to make is if you don't already have it, make sure

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:34.720
to grab the app.

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:38.919
This is where you can find all the information about what's going on, including the talks

00:00:38.919 --> 00:00:41.000
and all the other things that are happening.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:44.480
This is also where you can find a link to our Slido.

00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:49.080
This is where you will ask questions of the speakers, and it also has a link to a Discord

00:00:49.080 --> 00:00:54.919
if you want to engage with any of the other participants online or in person.

00:00:55.040 --> 00:01:00.520
New this year, we also have a really fun competition, both online and in person.

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:06.400
Do some fun activities around conf, collect points, and you can get some pretty cool swag

00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:09.720
at the end of it.

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:13.599
On your way to this keynote, you've all already walked through the lounge.

00:01:13.599 --> 00:01:18.519
This is the place if you want to ask questions about Posit, about our products, our open

00:01:18.519 --> 00:01:21.239
source packages, whatever you want.

00:01:21.239 --> 00:01:24.440
New this year, we also have a bunch of live demos going on.

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:27.839
Again, you can find out about those in the app.

00:01:27.839 --> 00:01:34.400
This is a great way if you want to find out what's new with Posit products this year.

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:39.680
But at Posit Conf, we also want to make sure that everyone feels safe, comfortable, and

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:41.279
welcome.

00:01:41.279 --> 00:01:45.160
And to that end, when you registered, one of the things you did was sign a code of conduct.

00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:46.919
That's really important to us.

00:01:46.919 --> 00:01:51.919
And if at any point you feel unsafe or notice anyone else may be feeling unsafe, please

00:01:51.919 --> 00:01:54.639
reach out to any Posit employee.

00:01:54.639 --> 00:02:01.839
You can also go to the registration desk or email conf at Posit.co.

00:02:01.839 --> 00:02:06.120
If you want to know how to recognize a Posit employee, well, you can spot us by our t-shirts.

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:10.399
Apart from me, obviously.

00:02:10.399 --> 00:02:15.600
And we've done a bunch of things to hopefully make you feel comfortable.

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:20.360
So please respect the keep your distance pins or the hugs okay pins.

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:24.240
If you see someone wearing a red lanyard, that means they prefer not to be photographed.

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:26.320
So please keep them out of any photos.

00:02:26.320 --> 00:02:30.720
And finally, everyone has their pronouns listed on their badges.

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:34.360
We also have a bunch of rooms available to you, regardless of whether that's a quiet

00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:37.759
zone just to hang out, whether you want to meditate or pray.

00:02:37.759 --> 00:02:43.179
We have a lactation room and gender-neutral bathrooms on every floor.

00:02:43.179 --> 00:02:48.440
And that brings me to really the only rule of Posit Conf, and that's the Pac-Man rule.

00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:53.360
Whenever you are standing in a circle with your friends, please make sure to leave Pac-Man's

00:02:53.360 --> 00:02:57.160
mouth open so new people can join your group.

00:02:57.160 --> 00:03:01.399
We want Posit Conf to feel welcoming to everyone, regardless of whether it's your fifth Posit

00:03:01.399 --> 00:03:04.100
Conf or your first Posit Conf.

00:03:04.100 --> 00:03:08.360
And I would kind of encourage you, if you're a Posit Conf veteran, you know, please do

00:03:08.360 --> 00:03:09.360
your best.

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:11.860
Like if you see someone hanging out and they look a bit lonely, you know, go up and strike

00:03:11.860 --> 00:03:14.059
out a conversation with them.

00:03:14.059 --> 00:03:18.580
Please take that as like your kind of mission from me to make everyone feel as welcome here

00:03:18.580 --> 00:03:21.139
as possible.

00:03:21.139 --> 00:03:25.119
If you're looking for like-minded individuals, a great way to find those people is our Birds

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:27.619
of a Feather session happening at lunch.

00:03:27.619 --> 00:03:29.699
You can spot them with the big flags.

00:03:29.699 --> 00:03:33.419
New this year, you can also create your own Birds of a Feather session.

00:03:33.419 --> 00:03:41.179
You'll find an easel with some stickies outside the entrance to the dining room.

00:03:41.179 --> 00:03:44.380
Now I don't know about you, but one of the things I am most excited about at this Posit

00:03:44.380 --> 00:03:47.419
Conf is our evening event at the Georgia Aquarium.

00:03:47.419 --> 00:03:48.660
It is an amazing aquarium.

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:50.619
It is going to be so much fun.

00:03:50.619 --> 00:03:55.059
The one thing I want to point out is please, please don't forget to bring your badge.

00:03:55.059 --> 00:03:58.979
We cannot let you in without it.

00:03:58.979 --> 00:04:04.220
So without much further ado, I would like to introduce our first keynote speaker, Jonathan

00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:05.220
McPherson.

00:04:05.220 --> 00:04:08.979
Jonathan is a long-term colleague of mine at Posit.

00:04:08.979 --> 00:04:15.460
And as you probably, as you may know, I like to write little poems about our keynote speakers

00:04:15.460 --> 00:04:19.940
with the help of AI, because I'm not very good at poems.

00:04:19.940 --> 00:04:27.540
Jonathan submitted the shortest bio ever for a keynote speaker, so Jonathan is just going

00:04:27.540 --> 00:04:31.820
to get a couple of haiku.

00:04:31.820 --> 00:04:37.339
Architect of code, Jonathan builds Positron, visions made precise.

00:04:37.339 --> 00:04:43.299
At RStudio's heart, he helped shape enduring tools guiding many hands.

00:04:43.299 --> 00:04:48.380
From Redmonds to now, wisdom gathered through the years, foundations endure.

00:04:48.380 --> 00:04:51.179
Please join me in welcoming Jonathan.

00:04:51.179 --> 00:05:03.859
Good morning, everyone.

00:05:03.859 --> 00:05:07.059
So like Hadley said, my name is Jonathan.

00:05:07.059 --> 00:05:10.140
And today we're going to talk about data science tools.

00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:17.799
But before we really get into it, I'd like to show you a picture of my brain.

00:05:17.799 --> 00:05:20.459
This is a knowledge graph.

00:05:20.459 --> 00:05:21.899
It's made up of notes.

00:05:21.899 --> 00:05:26.940
I've taken notes all of my life, but I first started doing it a little bit more obsessively

00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:29.700
back in 2016.

00:05:29.700 --> 00:05:35.660
And in this knowledge graph, every little dot that you see is a note that I took.

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:39.619
Every connection between dots is a connection between notes.

00:05:39.619 --> 00:05:43.779
And so this is kind of a picture of all those notes put together.

00:05:43.779 --> 00:05:47.739
If you look at this picture, you'll probably see a couple of clumps starting to emerge

00:05:47.739 --> 00:05:49.980
of notes that are related to each other.

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:52.660
This one over here, for example, is books that I've read.

00:05:52.660 --> 00:05:54.380
I like to read.

00:05:54.380 --> 00:05:56.940
This one over here is people I've interviewed.

00:05:56.940 --> 00:06:03.140
And I think this little one up here may be house projects that I will never finish.

00:06:03.140 --> 00:06:05.820
This graph comes from a program called Obsidian.

00:06:05.820 --> 00:06:09.660
Before Obsidian, I used a program called Vimwiki.

00:06:09.660 --> 00:06:15.380
But over the last ten years, as I've been accumulating all these notes, I noticed that

00:06:15.660 --> 00:06:20.260
something was happening to the way that I think and process information.

00:06:20.260 --> 00:06:26.260
In particular, I noticed that I had stopped thinking and then writing, and started using

00:06:26.260 --> 00:06:28.779
writing as a way to think.

00:06:28.779 --> 00:06:33.899
In particular, moving to thinking by writing.

00:06:33.899 --> 00:06:37.940
This tool actually did something to my brain.

00:06:37.940 --> 00:06:41.380
I'm not the first person to notice something like this happening.

00:06:41.380 --> 00:06:44.420
Another person who noticed this happening was this guy.

00:06:44.459 --> 00:06:46.459
This is Friedrich Nietzsche.

00:06:46.459 --> 00:06:48.940
He is famous for two things.

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:54.420
First of all, for being one of the most influential German philosophers of the 19th century.

00:06:54.420 --> 00:06:59.739
And secondly, for having an absolutely stupendous mustache.

00:06:59.739 --> 00:07:04.260
I wish that I could grow something as good as this.

00:07:04.260 --> 00:07:08.980
Back in the year 1881, Nietzsche's eyesight began to fail him.

00:07:08.980 --> 00:07:12.079
That was a real problem, because Nietzsche was an author.

00:07:12.079 --> 00:07:15.640
He wrote his books, and he wrote them longhand.

00:07:15.640 --> 00:07:20.959
Because he was unable to see what he was writing, he was compelled to purchase a typewriter

00:07:20.959 --> 00:07:22.440
in order to continue writing.

00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:23.640
This is the typewriter that he got.

00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:27.600
This is called the Malling-Hansen writing ball.

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:34.079
It may already be familiar to those of you who love ergonomic keyboards.

00:07:34.079 --> 00:07:41.559
As Nietzsche began to write with this thing, it actually had an effect on what he wrote.

00:07:42.040 --> 00:07:44.040
Critics also noticed this.

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:49.839
Nietzsche's first book that he wrote after he got this typewriter was called The Gay Science.

00:07:49.839 --> 00:07:53.119
One critic noted that it changed his prose.

00:07:53.119 --> 00:07:59.119
It said that he changed his prose from arguments to aphorisms, and from thoughts to puns, and

00:07:59.119 --> 00:08:02.920
from rhetoric to more of a telegram style.

00:08:02.920 --> 00:08:05.079
Nietzsche himself noticed this as well.

00:08:05.079 --> 00:08:08.600
It led him to make this observation, which I think is very profound.

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:16.839
He said that our writing tools are also working on our thoughts.

00:08:16.839 --> 00:08:20.640
If this is true, then it means that tools are not really interchangeable.

00:08:20.640 --> 00:08:26.239
I think in the world of data, in the world of software, we live in a world very full

00:08:26.239 --> 00:08:30.440
of symbols and manipulations, and it's easy to think that one tool can just kind of be

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:35.359
plugged in and substituted for another as some kind of layer of abstraction.

00:08:35.359 --> 00:08:38.840
But in this talk, I'm going to argue that that's actually not the case.

00:08:38.840 --> 00:08:40.840
Tools actually change the output.

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:44.880
This would be a very different talk if I gave it with PowerPoint, for example, instead of

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:45.880
Keynote here.

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:51.359
I'm going to argue that the tools that you use and the tools that you make matter quite

00:08:51.359 --> 00:08:52.799
a lot.

00:08:52.799 --> 00:08:58.840
But I'm going to guess you did not come here to learn about ergonomic typewriters nor mustaches.

00:08:58.840 --> 00:09:02.799
We came here to talk about data science, so let's talk about our studio.

00:09:02.799 --> 00:09:08.359
I had the immense honor of joining our studio back in 2013.

00:09:08.359 --> 00:09:11.039
This is what our website looked like back then.

00:09:11.039 --> 00:09:16.840
At the time, we were a very small company, about 10 people, and I was so excited to tell

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:21.440
all my friends and family about my new job at this little startup, but everyone that

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:25.919
I told, all my friends and family, when I told them about my new job, they all asked

00:09:25.919 --> 00:09:30.979
me exactly the same question, and I would guess it's the same question that you've heard

00:09:30.979 --> 00:09:39.659
from many of your friends and family, namely, what is RStudio?

00:09:39.659 --> 00:09:41.500
You've probably gotten this at some point in your life.

00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:50.099
So, that was 2013, you know, fast forward now to 2025, and RStudio has never done better.

00:09:50.099 --> 00:09:56.020
Just this year, in 2025, we crossed over 5 million runs of the RStudio IDE every week.

00:09:56.020 --> 00:10:00.140
I just want to call out a couple of interesting things about this graph that you might have

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:01.140
noticed.

00:10:01.140 --> 00:10:03.940
One of them is that it's really seasonal, you know.

00:10:03.940 --> 00:10:09.059
If you look at the graph, you can kind of see a dip in the summertime and a really big

00:10:09.059 --> 00:10:11.260
dip around Christmastime.

00:10:11.260 --> 00:10:15.299
RStudio is used a lot in work environments and academic environments, which kind of explains

00:10:15.299 --> 00:10:16.659
this.

00:10:16.659 --> 00:10:21.859
The other really interesting thing about these dips around the holidays is that, I don't

00:10:21.859 --> 00:10:25.500
know if you noticed this, they don't go all the way to zero.

00:10:26.500 --> 00:10:30.340
In fact, if you look at the axis here, this thing starts at 2 million runs.

00:10:30.340 --> 00:10:40.419
So, some of you are using RStudio on Christmas, and so, whoever you are, you're awesome.

00:10:40.419 --> 00:10:45.219
So I had the huge privilege of having a front row seat to the growth of RStudio during this

00:10:45.219 --> 00:10:49.739
time, and so, for the rest of this talk, I want to share about some things that we learned

00:10:49.739 --> 00:10:54.099
about making software and data science tools.

00:10:54.099 --> 00:10:59.059
I'll talk a bit about how we applied those learnings to Positron, and how you can also

00:10:59.059 --> 00:11:01.820
apply them to your own data science tools.

00:11:01.820 --> 00:11:07.619
So, the first thing I want to talk about is making tools for people, because at the end

00:11:07.619 --> 00:11:12.039
of the day, people are one of the only things that matter.

00:11:12.039 --> 00:11:14.979
Making tools for people might seem kind of obvious, but I think you have probably used

00:11:14.979 --> 00:11:21.500
a tool that seems like it was perhaps designed by and for an octopus.

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:23.440
These things exist.

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:26.479
So the first thing you've got to do if you want to make tools for people is you need

00:11:26.479 --> 00:11:27.760
to listen to them.

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:34.280
And again, I think this seems very obvious, but especially as organizational size and

00:11:34.280 --> 00:11:37.520
complexity grows, this can be kind of hard to do.

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:38.520
Here's a real life example.

00:11:38.520 --> 00:11:40.719
So I used to work at this company.

00:11:40.719 --> 00:11:43.760
I don't think I can say its name for legal reasons, but let's just say that it rhymes

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:47.919
with Microsoft.

00:11:47.919 --> 00:11:53.679
And our users wanted to store multiple values in one database cell.

00:11:53.679 --> 00:11:56.719
We made a desktop software product.

00:11:56.719 --> 00:12:01.640
And you can maybe make your own conclusions about whether or not this is a good idea.

00:12:01.640 --> 00:12:03.479
But it is what people wanted to do.

00:12:03.479 --> 00:12:08.119
And so, you know, they told the sales team, hey, I'd like to buy the product if only it

00:12:08.119 --> 00:12:12.640
had the feature to store multiple values in one database cell.

00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:16.239
And the sales and marketing team, of course, had to talk to the account rep and say, hey,

00:12:16.239 --> 00:12:20.799
we're having a hard time selling this without this multiple values in one database cell

00:12:20.799 --> 00:12:21.799
thing.

00:12:21.799 --> 00:12:25.960
Of course, they then needed to talk to the product planning team.

00:12:25.960 --> 00:12:30.039
And on the game of telephone went, you know, they've got to talk to product management.

00:12:30.039 --> 00:12:32.719
You know, product management needs to talk to the engineering lead.

00:12:32.719 --> 00:12:40.440
And finally, we actually get to the engineer, i.e. me, who's actually going to do this work.

00:12:40.440 --> 00:12:46.719
This whole process took, I don't know, maybe about two years, right?

00:12:46.719 --> 00:12:47.719
That's a long time.

00:12:47.719 --> 00:12:53.840
You know, fast forward to, you know, 2013 when I joined RStudio, and I'll probably never

00:12:53.840 --> 00:12:54.840
forget this experience.

00:12:54.840 --> 00:12:57.719
It's one of my first weeks at RStudio.

00:12:57.719 --> 00:13:00.440
And I was on our discussion forums.

00:13:00.440 --> 00:13:04.599
And somebody mentioned that they had found a bug in the data viewer.

00:13:04.599 --> 00:13:11.359
And I suddenly realized that all those people that were between me and the person my software

00:13:11.359 --> 00:13:14.320
was being written for were gone.

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:18.919
I could actually just go and just fix the problem.

00:13:18.919 --> 00:13:21.520
And this whole process took, like, maybe about two days.

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:25.640
So I guess my first piece of advice here is that you should connect the people who make

00:13:25.640 --> 00:13:30.719
the tool directly to the people who use the tool.

00:13:30.719 --> 00:13:36.559
This, again, is easier in a 10-person startup than it is when your company gets big.

00:13:36.559 --> 00:13:41.640
And this has been true, you know, almost as long as we've had technology companies.

00:13:41.640 --> 00:13:44.799
Some of you might remember the movie Office Space, where you have...

00:13:44.799 --> 00:13:49.239
Maybe you have someone at your company that kind of thinks that this is their role.

00:13:49.239 --> 00:13:55.960
They kind of interface between customers and engineers.

00:13:55.960 --> 00:14:00.200
And some people almost think it's some kind of law of physics that, like, the time of

00:14:00.200 --> 00:14:04.520
communication is, like, some, like, computable function of, like, your number of employees

00:14:04.520 --> 00:14:07.840
times, like, your layers of management and so forth.

00:14:07.840 --> 00:14:10.000
But I'm here to tell you this actually doesn't have to be true.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:11.659
It's not a law of physics.

00:14:11.659 --> 00:14:14.359
You can actually connect these groups of people.

00:14:14.359 --> 00:14:18.559
In fact, it's one of the things that we've tried to do at Posit as the company has grown.

00:14:18.559 --> 00:14:21.099
I think we're now maybe, like, 350 people.

00:14:21.099 --> 00:14:27.679
And if you, today, for example, go to Positron's discussion forum and you start a new, like,

00:14:27.679 --> 00:14:34.440
written thread on Positron, you will get a response, probably within a day, from an

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:38.080
actual person who works on Positron.

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:42.599
These people over here, with a couple of exceptions, are literally Positron engineers who work

00:14:42.599 --> 00:14:44.239
on it.

00:14:44.239 --> 00:14:47.520
This is a thing that you can do.

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:51.280
So it's really important to bring together the people that are using your software with

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:52.880
the people that are making it.

00:14:52.880 --> 00:14:56.320
Like, that direction connection is invaluable.

00:14:56.320 --> 00:15:02.599
But listening to your users alone can actually result in really bad software.

00:15:02.599 --> 00:15:06.320
And here's how this happens.

00:15:06.320 --> 00:15:09.440
Users approach you with feedback.

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:11.960
You listen to them.

00:15:11.960 --> 00:15:14.820
You do what they asked you to do.

00:15:14.820 --> 00:15:18.799
You built exactly the right tool.

00:15:18.799 --> 00:15:21.520
This is how a lot of people kind of approach software development.

00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:26.719
And we've learned that this actually is not always effective.

00:15:26.719 --> 00:15:27.719
And here's why.

00:15:27.719 --> 00:15:31.400
So we're all, I think, statisticians in the audience.

00:15:31.400 --> 00:15:36.760
Can anyone tell me a problem or a bias that might creep in with the very first step of

00:15:36.760 --> 00:15:37.760
this process?

00:15:37.760 --> 00:15:38.760
Anyone?

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:43.239
Got an anecdotal, yeah?

00:15:43.239 --> 00:15:46.260
I would argue that this is a sampling bias.

00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:47.679
You know, if you...

00:15:47.679 --> 00:15:50.919
This is sort of like having a survey.

00:15:50.919 --> 00:15:56.400
And the first question being, do you love responding to surveys?

00:15:56.400 --> 00:16:01.640
You know, if you only listen to the users who approach you, you are actually going to

00:16:01.640 --> 00:16:08.640
get a very not representative sample of all of the users who are using your tool.

00:16:08.640 --> 00:16:12.239
Let me show you a very specific example from RStudio.

00:16:12.239 --> 00:16:18.520
So if you go on RStudio today and you look at the GitHub issues in RStudio and just sort

00:16:18.520 --> 00:16:24.080
them by the ones that people want the most, you'll find that the most upvoted issue, number

00:16:24.080 --> 00:16:31.880
one, with 104 upvotes, is support for more Linux packaging systems.

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:35.760
And so it seems like this is the number one thing that users want us to do.

00:16:35.760 --> 00:16:38.559
And this is actually a really great idea.

00:16:38.559 --> 00:16:41.640
But I'll point out that we should consider the source.

00:16:41.640 --> 00:16:44.539
You know, where are we looking at this?

00:16:44.539 --> 00:16:49.780
This is our GitHub issue tracker, which means that everybody on it is a GitHub user.

00:16:49.780 --> 00:16:54.859
And GitHub users, as some of you may know, actually tend to prefer alternative operating

00:16:54.859 --> 00:16:55.859
systems.

00:16:55.859 --> 00:17:02.940
You want to guess how many Linux users as a percentage there are of RStudio?

00:17:02.940 --> 00:17:05.619
It's about 5%.

00:17:05.619 --> 00:17:08.939
So again, if you use Linux, this is not a dunk on you.

00:17:08.939 --> 00:17:09.939
You are awesome.

00:17:09.939 --> 00:17:11.579
This feature is a great idea.

00:17:12.060 --> 00:17:16.500
What I want to point out here is that if you only listen to the loudest voices in the room

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:20.300
and you only listen to the people that come and talk to you, you're actually not going

00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:23.339
to build a product that's good for everybody.

00:17:23.339 --> 00:17:29.420
It's not really enough to simply listen to your users.

00:17:29.420 --> 00:17:33.819
So when you listen to them, you can introduce another kind of bias.

00:17:33.819 --> 00:17:36.339
I would just call this one missing values.

00:17:36.339 --> 00:17:41.979
Because even though users will talk to you, it's also true that users mostly don't know

00:17:41.979 --> 00:17:44.420
what they want.

00:17:44.420 --> 00:17:48.380
You know, some of my favorite features to work on in RStudio have been features that

00:17:48.380 --> 00:17:51.540
literally nobody asked for.

00:17:51.540 --> 00:17:54.099
This is one that I worked on a few years back.

00:17:54.099 --> 00:17:56.060
It was one of my favorite little pet projects.

00:17:56.060 --> 00:17:59.000
It became a very popular feature.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:00.880
But literally no one asked for this.

00:18:00.880 --> 00:18:03.500
Your users don't necessarily know what they want.

00:18:03.500 --> 00:18:08.699
And so you need to kind of fill in the blanks when you're listening to them.

00:18:08.699 --> 00:18:11.739
So there's selection bias in the first step.

00:18:11.739 --> 00:18:13.859
In the second step, you can have some missing values.

00:18:13.859 --> 00:18:17.060
Users might not know what they want.

00:18:17.060 --> 00:18:22.579
Anyone have an idea of what can go wrong in the third step here?

00:18:22.579 --> 00:18:23.859
Absolutely nothing.

00:18:23.859 --> 00:18:27.660
This part is okay.

00:18:27.660 --> 00:18:32.579
So if you want to avoid this bias, what you need to do is actually watch people use your

00:18:32.660 --> 00:18:33.660
tool.

00:18:33.660 --> 00:18:34.660
And I promise you.

00:18:34.660 --> 00:18:40.260
I promise you if you watch people use your tool, you will always be surprised 100% of

00:18:40.260 --> 00:18:41.260
the time.

00:18:41.260 --> 00:18:44.739
People do things that you have no idea that they would do.

00:18:44.739 --> 00:18:46.339
I just want to be clear here.

00:18:46.339 --> 00:18:51.219
We do not collect telemetry on individual users at Posit.

00:18:51.219 --> 00:18:53.339
That's just not our thing.

00:18:53.339 --> 00:18:58.979
So everything that I'm about to say is based on things that were shared on YouTube.

00:18:58.979 --> 00:19:05.140
Turns out people really love recording themselves using RStudio and putting it on YouTube.

00:19:05.140 --> 00:19:09.420
Observations of colleagues and so forth.

00:19:09.420 --> 00:19:13.660
Here's an example of somebody using RStudio on YouTube.

00:19:13.660 --> 00:19:19.180
One of the things that we noticed when we watched people using RStudio is this.

00:19:19.180 --> 00:19:21.699
So you can put your hand up or not.

00:19:21.699 --> 00:19:28.239
But how many of you have ever opened RStudio, one of the most advanced statistical environments

00:19:28.239 --> 00:19:35.719
ever invented, in order to add two numbers?

00:19:35.719 --> 00:19:36.719
People love doing this.

00:19:36.719 --> 00:19:40.079
Yeah, they treat it like a calculator, right?

00:19:40.079 --> 00:19:41.680
This is a thing that people love.

00:19:41.680 --> 00:19:45.280
And you'll never see this on GitHub issues because no one's going to open an issue and

00:19:45.280 --> 00:19:49.119
say, I wish this thing was a calculator.

00:19:49.119 --> 00:19:54.040
And so by watching people do this, we actually were able to bring that same feature to Positron.

00:19:54.040 --> 00:20:00.680
So when you open up Positron, you'll notice that it has exactly the same feature.

00:20:00.680 --> 00:20:05.939
When you open up, it will try very hard to make sure that it is a calculator.

00:20:05.939 --> 00:20:09.160
You can type stuff into it and get an evaluation.

00:20:09.160 --> 00:20:12.520
Again, just kind of based on watching people.

00:20:12.520 --> 00:20:14.920
The same thing is true of the data viewer, right?

00:20:14.920 --> 00:20:19.239
So RStudio has got a really nice data viewer.

00:20:19.239 --> 00:20:24.079
And one thing we noticed from watching people use the system is that people have this data

00:20:24.079 --> 00:20:27.079
viewer open all the time.

00:20:27.079 --> 00:20:28.079
It's a fixture.

00:20:28.079 --> 00:20:33.760
In fact, the amount of time that people spend using this data viewer is way out of proportion

00:20:33.760 --> 00:20:37.520
to the amount of time that we spent making this data viewer.

00:20:37.520 --> 00:20:43.839
This thing is the result of maybe like two or three months of effort.

00:20:43.839 --> 00:20:48.479
And so based on that observation, when we built Positron, we were like, we are going

00:20:48.479 --> 00:20:52.239
to make a really, really good data viewer.

00:20:52.239 --> 00:20:54.760
You can go play with this today in the Positron lounge if you're interested.

00:20:54.760 --> 00:20:58.839
But this thing has support for a million rows and a million columns.

00:20:58.839 --> 00:21:00.439
It's super high performance.

00:21:00.439 --> 00:21:02.680
There's really nice column profiles.

00:21:02.680 --> 00:21:06.520
It has excellent searching and sorting and filtering and row and column pitting and all

00:21:06.520 --> 00:21:08.160
kinds of great stuff.

00:21:08.160 --> 00:21:11.959
And again, this is based on the observation that the data viewer is where people spend

00:21:11.959 --> 00:21:12.959
a lot of their time.

00:21:13.079 --> 00:21:18.560
It's not something you can learn by just listening to the problems that people report.

00:21:18.560 --> 00:21:22.479
So it's really important to listen to people and to watch them.

00:21:22.479 --> 00:21:26.520
And another thing you've got to do if you want to make tools like this is you need to

00:21:26.520 --> 00:21:31.920
take things that are complicated and make them simple.

00:21:31.920 --> 00:21:34.560
Who wants to see that keyword again?

00:21:34.560 --> 00:21:36.359
Yeah.

00:21:36.359 --> 00:21:40.199
So again, this is the Mallinghansen writing ball.

00:21:40.199 --> 00:21:43.719
And I just want to invite you to stare at this thing for a minute.

00:21:43.719 --> 00:21:48.959
And I think the longer you look at it, the more complicated this thing looks.

00:21:48.959 --> 00:21:53.959
I could probably tell my children that this is a steam powered radio telescope.

00:21:53.959 --> 00:21:57.160
And I think they would believe me.

00:21:57.160 --> 00:22:01.160
But if you use a keyboard today, it actually probably looks a lot more like the keyboard

00:22:01.160 --> 00:22:05.239
on the right than the one on the left.

00:22:05.239 --> 00:22:11.239
And I just ask you, you know, where did that complexity go?

00:22:11.239 --> 00:22:19.119
And someone much smarter than me once pointed out that complexity is a little bit like entropy,

00:22:19.119 --> 00:22:22.160
which is to say that you can never get rid of it.

00:22:22.160 --> 00:22:28.560
And the best you can ever hope to do is just kind of move it around.

00:22:28.560 --> 00:22:33.680
In fact, if you look at this somewhat simpler keyboard, you'll find that it's not actually

00:22:33.680 --> 00:22:34.680
simpler.

00:22:35.119 --> 00:22:38.599
It's considerably more complicated than that thing that Nietzsche was using.

00:22:38.599 --> 00:22:41.520
It's just that all the complexity is hidden from you.

00:22:41.520 --> 00:22:44.319
The complexity is over there.

00:22:44.319 --> 00:22:47.560
It's hidden where you don't have to deal with it.

00:22:47.560 --> 00:22:53.040
The tool has taken the complexity away from you and kind of embedded it in the tool itself.

00:22:53.040 --> 00:22:57.280
It's probably not too hard to see where I'm going here with data science tools.

00:22:57.280 --> 00:23:01.400
An example from the RStudio world is breakpoints.

00:23:01.400 --> 00:23:08.400
In RStudio, you can click on a line number and you get a cute little red dot.

00:23:08.400 --> 00:23:14.780
And the next time that line of code runs, it will stop there and you can look around.

00:23:14.780 --> 00:23:18.640
This functionality is built on a lot of complexity.

00:23:18.640 --> 00:23:25.880
In fact, did anyone know that R itself has a set breakpoint function?

00:23:25.880 --> 00:23:31.680
I'm guessing that most of you did not know this because even though R has this, it's

00:23:31.680 --> 00:23:34.160
really complicated to use.

00:23:34.160 --> 00:23:38.479
RStudio takes that complexity away and puts it in the tool so you can just kind of click

00:23:38.479 --> 00:23:40.400
in the gutter.

00:23:40.400 --> 00:23:42.640
Search is another good example of this.

00:23:42.640 --> 00:23:50.319
If you use a search or a search and replace in RStudio or here this is Positron, the interface

00:23:50.319 --> 00:23:52.199
almost could not be simpler.

00:23:52.199 --> 00:23:56.520
You just literally type what you're looking for and you see a list of results.

00:23:56.520 --> 00:24:00.319
And again, this is not something that you have to use an IDE to do.

00:24:00.319 --> 00:24:03.959
You can do this at the command line with something like grep.

00:24:03.959 --> 00:24:10.199
But if you really want to do this well, you need to understand things like text encodings

00:24:10.199 --> 00:24:15.400
and recursion and ignore files and regular expressions.

00:24:15.400 --> 00:24:17.719
And we take all that complexity away from you.

00:24:17.719 --> 00:24:21.400
We put it in the tool so you can just type a word.

00:24:21.400 --> 00:24:26.920
And so that's kind of the thing that you need to remember here is, when at all possible.

00:24:26.920 --> 00:24:31.199
You can't get rid of complexity, but you can take it away from people and put it in your

00:24:31.199 --> 00:24:34.280
tool.

00:24:34.280 --> 00:24:38.719
So as we move into the next session, I'd like to ask you if you have ever used a tool that

00:24:38.719 --> 00:24:43.319
made you feel dumb.

00:24:43.319 --> 00:24:44.319
I love this.

00:24:44.319 --> 00:24:46.359
This is a piece of art, not a real fork.

00:24:46.359 --> 00:24:52.079
This is a collection from a collection by a Greek artist named Katerina Kamprani.

00:24:52.079 --> 00:24:53.400
And I love this thing, right?

00:24:53.400 --> 00:24:57.160
Because you can almost imagine how this could happen.

00:24:57.160 --> 00:25:02.319
You know, you could imagine someone coming to you and saying, hey, we work at a company

00:25:02.319 --> 00:25:04.719
that makes silverware.

00:25:04.719 --> 00:25:09.280
These forks are great, but could you make them a little more flexible?

00:25:09.280 --> 00:25:12.040
Or you know, wine glasses, they've been done.

00:25:12.040 --> 00:25:16.800
What if we made them, I don't know, more collaborative?

00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:25.520
Or you know, like, we make silverware, but man, I really wish it was more sturdy.

00:25:25.520 --> 00:25:29.400
And I'm sure you've used tools that were made this way, right?

00:25:29.400 --> 00:25:34.560
They're optimizing for one particular attribute.

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:40.439
And certainly this is sturdier than regular flatware, but it's also really uncomfortable

00:25:40.439 --> 00:25:42.400
to use.

00:25:42.400 --> 00:25:47.319
And so I think a lot of times as toolmakers, we make tools that are designed to achieve

00:25:47.319 --> 00:25:51.280
our own goals and we kind of forget that we're making things really uncomfortable for people

00:25:51.280 --> 00:25:52.959
using them.

00:25:52.959 --> 00:25:58.920
It is really important to meet people where they are.

00:25:58.920 --> 00:26:02.040
And again, let me give you a couple of concrete examples of this.

00:26:02.040 --> 00:26:07.800
For example, you may have heard it said unto you that you should make a separate folder

00:26:07.800 --> 00:26:09.640
for each project.

00:26:09.640 --> 00:26:12.079
This is really good advice.

00:26:12.079 --> 00:26:17.160
If you make a separate folder for each project, you will be able to isolate dependencies.

00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:20.479
You'll be much more successful with source control software.

00:26:20.479 --> 00:26:25.439
You'll be able to reuse templates and all kinds of other great stuff.

00:26:25.439 --> 00:26:29.280
This is almost unilaterally a good idea.

00:26:29.280 --> 00:26:32.839
But we don't make you do it.

00:26:32.839 --> 00:26:37.199
Both RStudio and Positron open up in this mode where there's no project and they don't

00:26:37.199 --> 00:26:39.319
try to force you to make one.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:46.119
And this is because we've learned that sometimes people, when they open up the software, maybe

00:26:46.119 --> 00:26:48.959
they're not looking to use a project.

00:26:48.959 --> 00:26:52.839
Maybe they just want to add two numbers.

00:26:52.839 --> 00:26:55.319
Sometimes you just kind of want a quick scratch pad, right?

00:26:55.319 --> 00:27:00.319
A project is a good idea, but forcing users into that workflow from the get-go is not

00:27:00.319 --> 00:27:03.040
very ergonomic.

00:27:03.040 --> 00:27:04.839
Here's another thing you may have heard.

00:27:04.839 --> 00:27:09.520
You should start with a fresh workspace every time.

00:27:09.520 --> 00:27:10.520
You probably heard this.

00:27:10.520 --> 00:27:12.839
And this is very good advice.

00:27:12.839 --> 00:27:17.479
This makes sure that you're always recreating the data from scratch and not having these

00:27:17.479 --> 00:27:21.359
long-running things that you can't reproduce.

00:27:21.359 --> 00:27:25.199
But we don't make you do it.

00:27:25.199 --> 00:27:29.800
In RStudio, the current options, which you can argue whether these are the correct presets

00:27:29.800 --> 00:27:30.800
or not.

00:27:30.800 --> 00:27:33.280
Positron actually does this a little bit differently.

00:27:33.359 --> 00:27:35.839
We do not enforce this workflow.

00:27:35.839 --> 00:27:41.119
We do allow you to save and load it, again, because sometimes you're not building a beautiful

00:27:41.119 --> 00:27:43.280
monument to reproducibility.

00:27:43.280 --> 00:27:46.800
Sometimes you just need a little bit of a scratch pad.

00:27:46.800 --> 00:27:52.359
And so we've kind of compromised a little bit on enforcing reproducibility in order

00:27:52.359 --> 00:27:55.880
to make a tool that feels more ergonomic.

00:27:55.880 --> 00:27:57.479
Here's another thing you might have heard.

00:27:57.479 --> 00:28:00.800
Don't change the working directory.

00:28:00.800 --> 00:28:04.280
This is also very good advice.

00:28:04.280 --> 00:28:08.160
If you're manually changing the working directory, it usually implies that the code that you're

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:10.640
writing is not going to be very portable.

00:28:10.640 --> 00:28:12.920
It's going to have problems with paths.

00:28:12.920 --> 00:28:16.000
Generally speaking, you want to make sure you're computing your path from a project

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:18.119
root.

00:28:18.119 --> 00:28:23.839
But not only do we let you do this, we actually made a button that does it.

00:28:23.839 --> 00:28:29.800
Again, in the service of the fact that we understand that people need to do this.

00:28:29.800 --> 00:28:33.400
It's really important that your tools be ergonomic and sometimes at the expense of

00:28:33.400 --> 00:28:36.280
ideological purity.

00:28:36.280 --> 00:28:38.699
So it's really important to listen to people.

00:28:38.699 --> 00:28:45.239
It's really important that you make your tool easy to use and simple.

00:28:45.239 --> 00:28:49.000
Another thing that you've really got to do is empower your users.

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:55.160
Back in 2016, we created these things called RStudio add-ins.

00:28:55.160 --> 00:29:04.079
And the RStudio add-in API is actually fairly low-powered as extension APIs go.

00:29:04.079 --> 00:29:08.880
But the community took it and made just kind of an explosion of creativity with it.

00:29:08.880 --> 00:29:12.479
We have this, this is one of my favorite add-ins called Datapasta.

00:29:12.479 --> 00:29:16.199
What this thing does is it, you should try it if you haven't, it lets you copy data from

00:29:16.199 --> 00:29:22.099
anything on the web and paste it into RStudio and it turns it into R code that creates that

00:29:22.099 --> 00:29:24.160
same data set.

00:29:24.160 --> 00:29:28.959
There's one called Shortcuts that literally lets you make anything into an RStudio shortcut.

00:29:28.959 --> 00:29:31.640
There's a really nice one called RegExplain.

00:29:31.640 --> 00:29:35.560
And what this one does is explains regular expressions.

00:29:35.560 --> 00:29:37.280
There's a color picker one.

00:29:37.280 --> 00:29:40.319
There's a styler one for styling your R code.

00:29:40.319 --> 00:29:45.199
There's a theme assister and there's a bazillion of these.

00:29:45.199 --> 00:29:51.640
And the community has just really surprised us with their creativity.

00:29:51.640 --> 00:29:53.239
This is also true in VS Code land.

00:29:53.239 --> 00:29:57.920
And that is one of the reasons that Positron is built on VS Code is because VS Code has

00:29:57.920 --> 00:30:02.319
got something like 80,000 extensions.

00:30:02.319 --> 00:30:08.439
They have really managed to make it very easy for people to contribute experiences to the

00:30:08.439 --> 00:30:10.439
editor surface.

00:30:10.439 --> 00:30:15.560
And these extensions, they really run the gamut of possibility.

00:30:15.560 --> 00:30:21.920
All the way from something like a C and C++ development compilation and inspection environment

00:30:21.920 --> 00:30:30.520
to a cute little cat that you can adopt and put in your IDE.

00:30:30.520 --> 00:30:35.079
In fact, if you'll allow me to nerd out just a little bit, bear with me for a minute here.

00:30:35.079 --> 00:30:42.239
I think that VS Code's extension model is actually a core reason for it being so successful.

00:30:42.239 --> 00:30:49.800
Prior to VS Code, a lot of editors, and by the way, I blame Emacs for this, a lot of

00:30:49.800 --> 00:30:54.680
editors load their extensions right into the editor itself.

00:30:54.680 --> 00:31:00.880
Emacs started this trend, as far as I know, and it gives the extensions a lot of power

00:31:00.880 --> 00:31:06.640
and literally makes the editor something that you can extend infinitely in a way that's

00:31:06.640 --> 00:31:09.439
as native as the editor itself.

00:31:09.439 --> 00:31:11.239
Emacs actually is a really great IDE.

00:31:11.239 --> 00:31:14.160
It's just missing a good text editor.

00:31:14.160 --> 00:31:22.760
And this is the approach that Adam takes, for example, and the problem with this approach

00:31:22.760 --> 00:31:28.280
is that when you do this, you allow the extensions to compromise the core IDE experience.

00:31:28.280 --> 00:31:31.239
And so VS Code works a little differently.

00:31:31.239 --> 00:31:33.760
Extensions run actually separately from the IDE.

00:31:33.760 --> 00:31:38.040
They run in this thing called the extension host, and they only get to talk to the UI

00:31:38.040 --> 00:31:41.520
and what's effectively remote procedure calls.

00:31:41.520 --> 00:31:48.000
And this design has allowed VS Code, I think, to make a very good tradeoff between making

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:54.079
a system that is extensible by the community, but also having a reputation for reliability

00:31:54.079 --> 00:31:55.239
and performance.

00:31:55.239 --> 00:32:01.920
This is why VS Code has 80,000 extensions and is still fast, and it's one of the design

00:32:01.920 --> 00:32:04.959
principles that we adopted for Positron.

00:32:04.959 --> 00:32:10.520
So in Positron, we kind of took this idea and we extended it.

00:32:10.520 --> 00:32:16.119
Just like VS Code has an API that allows you to build extensions, Positron has that API.

00:32:16.119 --> 00:32:20.439
We also added another API that makes it possible to add language packs.

00:32:20.439 --> 00:32:26.760
So in Positron, the R and the Python systems are actually extensions.

00:32:26.760 --> 00:32:34.719
I find it's easiest to think of Positron as almost like a data science workbench that

00:32:34.719 --> 00:32:37.839
has these kind of core features like a data view and a console.

00:32:37.839 --> 00:32:42.599
And then R and Python are more like extensions that plug into that workbench and give you

00:32:42.599 --> 00:32:44.760
specific language capabilities.

00:32:44.760 --> 00:32:49.439
But this thing is built on an API that allows anyone to make these, and we hope that you

00:32:49.439 --> 00:32:54.800
as a community are able to take this thing and build your own creative solutions on top

00:32:54.800 --> 00:32:56.839
of it.

00:32:56.839 --> 00:33:00.439
This is another way that I like to think about this.

00:33:00.439 --> 00:33:06.839
If you think about the parts of the product that you build, certainly the core functionality

00:33:06.839 --> 00:33:09.319
is something that belongs inside your product.

00:33:09.319 --> 00:33:15.920
But if you allow users to build extensions to your system, what you'll find is that they

00:33:15.920 --> 00:33:20.959
can build out kind of this long-tail functionality that is not or maybe even shouldn't be part

00:33:20.959 --> 00:33:24.040
of the core of your system.

00:33:24.040 --> 00:33:28.640
So it is very important to give people the ability to extend your tool.

00:33:28.640 --> 00:33:32.599
I promise you will always be surprised at their creativity if you do this.

00:33:32.599 --> 00:33:39.880
Although it is possible to overdo this, I will say.

00:33:39.880 --> 00:33:43.079
So it's really important to make tools for people, but also for results.

00:33:43.079 --> 00:33:48.680
So if you think about the whole equation of like a person uses a tool, the thing that

00:33:48.680 --> 00:33:51.160
they make is a result, right?

00:33:51.160 --> 00:33:57.280
And when I say result here, I'm talking both about an artifact or an output like a PDF

00:33:57.280 --> 00:34:04.959
document or a PowerPoint presentation or a report, a dashboard, anything like that, as

00:34:04.959 --> 00:34:06.599
well as an effect, right?

00:34:06.599 --> 00:34:11.040
Less time searching for information or better organized information.

00:34:11.040 --> 00:34:14.840
Who wants to see that keyboard again?

00:34:14.840 --> 00:34:20.560
So I want to remind you what the effect of this thing was on the output or the result

00:34:20.560 --> 00:34:21.760
of Nietzsche's writing.

00:34:21.760 --> 00:34:28.719
It created aphorisms and puns and telegrams out of his writing.

00:34:28.719 --> 00:34:36.439
And so I think what this implies is that a tool's output is shaped by its design.

00:34:36.439 --> 00:34:41.399
And I would also argue, if you'll allow me to get philosophical for just a minute, that

00:34:41.399 --> 00:34:46.459
the world that we experience is actually made up of the output of many tools, like all those

00:34:46.459 --> 00:34:50.459
books that are out there that were written with that typewriter.

00:34:50.459 --> 00:34:55.860
But even like think about the stuff that you're experiencing right now, like these monitors,

00:34:55.860 --> 00:35:01.139
like this stage, the chair you're sitting in, your laptop, your landing gear, all these

00:35:01.139 --> 00:35:07.020
things are actually the end result of many, many tool outputs.

00:35:07.020 --> 00:35:11.260
And so if it's true that a tool's output is shaped by its design and the world we experience

00:35:11.260 --> 00:35:17.820
is made from the output of many tools, it follows that a tool is a statement about what

00:35:17.820 --> 00:35:20.500
you want the world to become.

00:35:20.500 --> 00:35:25.699
I think many of us in this audience are tool makers, and it's important to realize that

00:35:25.699 --> 00:35:29.379
the tools that we make, because again the world is made up of these things, are actually

00:35:29.379 --> 00:35:31.860
statements about how we want the world to be.

00:35:31.860 --> 00:35:36.139
Who wants to see that typewriter again?

00:35:36.139 --> 00:35:41.219
So I want you to think about what statement is this thing making about what it wants to

00:35:41.219 --> 00:35:44.139
the world to be.

00:35:44.139 --> 00:35:49.020
I would argue that what this thing is saying is that writing should be closer to thinking.

00:35:49.020 --> 00:35:53.459
You know, this thing removes a step between writing and thinking because you no longer

00:35:53.459 --> 00:35:56.860
need to form the letters by hand, you just press a button and the letter appears, right?

00:35:56.860 --> 00:36:02.379
It moves your thoughts closer to your output.

00:36:02.379 --> 00:36:06.979
And as a result, what you write becomes closer to what you think.

00:36:06.979 --> 00:36:10.379
Imagine something as simple as a garden variety leaf blower.

00:36:10.379 --> 00:36:13.979
This is also a tool that says something about the world, you know?

00:36:13.979 --> 00:36:20.419
You might think that this says something like, sidewalk should be clean, but what this tool

00:36:20.419 --> 00:36:25.659
actually says is that no one deserves to sleep after 6 a.m.

00:36:25.659 --> 00:36:30.020
Or even think about this VS Code Pets extension, right?

00:36:30.020 --> 00:36:32.159
What does this tool say about the world?

00:36:32.159 --> 00:36:33.659
What does this tool want the world to become?

00:36:34.219 --> 00:36:39.540
I would say this tool says the world should be more fun and whimsical, right?

00:36:39.540 --> 00:36:42.860
Even something as simple as this has a point of view.

00:36:42.860 --> 00:36:49.179
A few slides ago, I showed you this diagram of Positron's architecture.

00:36:49.179 --> 00:36:54.979
And this API that we made that lets you plug different languages into Positron is also

00:36:54.979 --> 00:36:55.979
a tool.

00:36:55.979 --> 00:37:01.580
And because it's a tool, it says something about what we want the world to be, right?

00:37:01.580 --> 00:37:08.020
We think that there should be room for many languages and they should work together.

00:37:08.020 --> 00:37:12.260
So I want to talk for a couple minutes about the tools at Positron and the things we want

00:37:12.260 --> 00:37:13.979
them to say to the world.

00:37:13.979 --> 00:37:18.020
One thing that our tools always want to say is that science should be reproducible.

00:37:18.020 --> 00:37:19.020
So I've worked on IDEs.

00:37:19.020 --> 00:37:22.419
Let me talk a minute about how we do that in our IDEs.

00:37:22.419 --> 00:37:26.219
For example, again, looking at RStudio's data viewer, you'll notice one thing that this

00:37:26.219 --> 00:37:30.020
data viewer doesn't have is an edit button.

00:37:30.020 --> 00:37:33.739
And the reason it doesn't have this isn't because no one's ever asked for it or because

00:37:33.739 --> 00:37:35.100
it wouldn't be handy.

00:37:35.100 --> 00:37:39.459
It's because it is so easy, if you have an edit button, to start editing your data by

00:37:39.459 --> 00:37:44.580
hand and creating a workflow that's not at all reproducible.

00:37:44.580 --> 00:37:45.899
I know you're thinking, wait a minute, Jonathan.

00:37:45.899 --> 00:37:49.020
A few slides ago, you told me to put in stuff that users want.

00:37:49.020 --> 00:37:51.899
And the truth is that this is not actually an easy decision.

00:37:51.899 --> 00:37:55.540
You kind of have to decide on the tradeoffs here.

00:37:55.540 --> 00:38:00.780
In Positron, we've tried hard to make this even more reproducible by adding a button

00:38:00.780 --> 00:38:06.580
that actually converts the sorting and filtering that you've done in the data viewer into code.

00:38:06.580 --> 00:38:10.820
So you can take the buttons that you clicked and the sorts and filters that you added and

00:38:10.820 --> 00:38:19.020
actually create code that does those same edits so that you do them again and again.

00:38:19.020 --> 00:38:24.459
I want to take you back for a minute just to RStudio Conf 2019.

00:38:24.459 --> 00:38:32.340
You may recall at the time, these low code and no code tools were kind of having a moment.

00:38:32.340 --> 00:38:39.340
And Tarif gave this presentation about basically just coming out in support of code and saying,

00:38:39.340 --> 00:38:40.340
we actually love code.

00:38:40.340 --> 00:38:41.340
It's repeatable.

00:38:41.340 --> 00:38:42.459
It's inspectable.

00:38:42.459 --> 00:38:43.699
It's reusable.

00:38:43.699 --> 00:38:44.699
It's diffable.

00:38:44.699 --> 00:38:49.840
And in the age of AI, I actually think a couple more bullets should be added here.

00:38:49.840 --> 00:38:52.899
Code is ingestible.

00:38:52.899 --> 00:38:54.939
Code is what these models read.

00:38:54.939 --> 00:39:00.860
And if you have expressed your tools and your workflow in the form of code, the models can

00:39:00.860 --> 00:39:04.139
actually read that code and understand what you're doing.

00:39:04.139 --> 00:39:11.500
Similarly, code is disgorgeable, is that a word?

00:39:11.500 --> 00:39:12.939
These models also write code.

00:39:12.939 --> 00:39:19.020
So if you are kind of embracing a code first data science workflow, you've actually kind

00:39:19.020 --> 00:39:24.139
of already positioned yourself to get the best out of what this new generation of AI

00:39:24.139 --> 00:39:26.300
tools has to offer.

00:39:26.300 --> 00:39:29.219
So code should be reproducible.

00:39:29.219 --> 00:39:30.219
How about this one?

00:39:30.219 --> 00:39:31.300
Science should be free and open.

00:39:31.300 --> 00:39:34.639
This is something you've heard us say a lot.

00:39:34.639 --> 00:39:40.060
When you hear it, you probably think a lot about our open source packages and models.

00:39:40.060 --> 00:39:42.739
But this is also true of our IDEs.

00:39:42.739 --> 00:39:46.600
You know, when we built RStudio, everything was kind of packaged into one unit, right?

00:39:46.600 --> 00:39:52.439
We have R execution and debugging and code formatting and all this stuff was kind of

00:39:52.439 --> 00:39:54.239
in one bit.

00:39:54.239 --> 00:39:59.320
But in Positron, we've tried to make the system more free and open.

00:39:59.320 --> 00:40:03.840
So again, I'd like to think of Positron as like a data science workbench.

00:40:03.840 --> 00:40:09.959
And for the R components of Positron, we actually built a couple of reusable systems that can

00:40:09.959 --> 00:40:12.000
be used outside of Positron.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:16.280
So Positron's code execution engine and like it's R formatted and so forth, they're actually

00:40:16.959 --> 00:40:22.639
separate subsystems that we've contributed to the community to use in other ways.

00:40:22.639 --> 00:40:24.479
This is not just theoretical.

00:40:24.479 --> 00:40:29.320
For example, I don't know if any of you use the Zed text editor, but if you go and look

00:40:29.320 --> 00:40:33.080
at how to run R code in Zed, what they'll tell you is to go get the ARC kernel, which

00:40:33.080 --> 00:40:41.320
is Positron's code execution engine, and plug it into Zed so you can run R code there.

00:40:41.320 --> 00:40:47.320
If you have used TreeSitter R, I'm guessing you think you haven't, but if you've ever

00:40:47.320 --> 00:40:51.280
looked for R code on GitHub in the last few months, you have.

00:40:51.280 --> 00:40:56.679
The R code navigation system on GitHub is actually powered in part by code that we wrote

00:40:56.679 --> 00:40:58.439
for Positron.

00:40:58.439 --> 00:41:02.080
We've contributed that back to the community and back to GitHub.

00:41:02.080 --> 00:41:04.560
The same thing is true of that R code formatter.

00:41:04.560 --> 00:41:10.439
So this is the VS code plug-in, you can get this today, it's on the marketplace.

00:41:10.439 --> 00:41:14.439
You can use Positron's code formatter inside of VS code, and you know what?

00:41:14.439 --> 00:41:17.560
You can also use it inside of RStudio.

00:41:17.560 --> 00:41:19.959
It works great there.

00:41:19.959 --> 00:41:25.000
And so I guess what I'm saying here is we really do believe that the universe of software

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:29.060
should be more free and open, and this is a statement that we want to make about the

00:41:29.060 --> 00:41:32.879
world with our tools.

00:41:32.879 --> 00:41:37.399
I just want to say one more thing here before we wrap up.

00:41:37.399 --> 00:41:43.600
I have kind of experienced a lot of feedback about what's going to happen to RStudio in

00:41:43.600 --> 00:41:47.679
the world of Positron, and people seem to think that we're going to remove RStudio

00:41:47.679 --> 00:41:50.959
in favor of Positron, which is not true.

00:41:50.959 --> 00:41:55.080
So let me kind of tell you how I think about this.

00:41:55.080 --> 00:41:57.600
This is the picture that kind of comes to my mind.

00:41:57.600 --> 00:42:03.199
If you're like me, you actually have both of these tools in your toolbox.

00:42:03.199 --> 00:42:09.439
I've got a Phillips screwdriver that I often reach for, but I also have one of these screwdrivers

00:42:09.439 --> 00:42:12.719
that has multiple bits that I can kind of swap out as I need.

00:42:12.719 --> 00:42:18.080
And the truth is that some of these things are useful or not at different times.

00:42:18.080 --> 00:42:25.679
One thing that is true about making tools is that as you make a tool more and more generic,

00:42:25.679 --> 00:42:31.000
it kind of becomes less and less good at any one particular thing.

00:42:31.399 --> 00:42:38.040
RStudio is a great tool for R in part because it only does R.

00:42:38.040 --> 00:42:43.239
It is very well built for that purpose, and if that is all you need, then it is always

00:42:43.239 --> 00:42:47.320
going to be a tool that's more like a Swiss army knife that's got a bunch of attachments

00:42:47.320 --> 00:42:49.120
hanging off of it.

00:42:49.120 --> 00:42:54.239
Sometimes you do need the Swiss army knife, and I often find myself reaching for Positron.

00:42:54.239 --> 00:43:00.320
But RStudio is very fit for purpose, and a lot of times when I'm reaching in my toolbox

00:43:00.320 --> 00:43:06.239
what I want is the tool built for that specific task.

00:43:06.239 --> 00:43:11.760
So just to kind of remind you of what I've talked about here, I think it's really important

00:43:11.760 --> 00:43:14.280
to make tools for people.

00:43:14.280 --> 00:43:19.000
You need to listen to them, you need to watch them, not in a creepy way.

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:23.479
You need to empower them.

00:43:23.479 --> 00:43:25.800
People are one of the most important components of a good tool.

00:43:25.800 --> 00:43:28.120
You need to make tools for results.

00:43:28.120 --> 00:43:33.639
I want you to remember that you need to shape the tool according to the good that you want

00:43:33.639 --> 00:43:35.840
it to do.

00:43:35.840 --> 00:43:39.639
And finally, if you literally remember nothing else from this keynote, this is the thing

00:43:39.639 --> 00:43:44.360
I want you to remember as a tool builder, and that is that a tool is a statement about

00:43:44.360 --> 00:43:47.560
what you want the world to become.

00:43:47.560 --> 00:43:54.479
As people who build tools, this is an enormous responsibility, but it is also a huge, huge

00:43:54.479 --> 00:43:55.479
privilege.

00:43:55.800 --> 00:43:59.360
And with that, I think we'll take some questions.

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:00.360
Thank you.

00:44:00.360 --> 00:44:01.360
Thanks, Jonathan.

00:44:01.360 --> 00:44:16.360
So if you want to ask any questions, you can ask them on Slido.

00:44:16.360 --> 00:44:19.000
Again, that link is in the conference app.

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:24.959
I am going to pick the questions based on the number of votes, plus whether I think

00:44:24.959 --> 00:44:25.959
they're cool or not.

00:44:25.959 --> 00:44:26.959
So I'm going to ask one.

00:44:26.959 --> 00:44:27.959
It's kind of a fun one.

00:44:27.959 --> 00:44:32.199
I didn't get so many votes, but I think it's interesting.

00:44:32.199 --> 00:44:37.000
What's the most surprising thing you've seen and that you never expected someone would

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:39.879
do with RStudio or Positron?

00:44:39.879 --> 00:44:44.719
The most surprising thing that I would never have expected anyone would do with RStudio

00:44:44.719 --> 00:44:46.719
and Positron.

00:44:46.719 --> 00:44:53.520
I think it's not too surprising to see the actual things that people do with it.

00:44:53.520 --> 00:44:59.479
I have been very surprised to see where people want to run this thing.

00:44:59.479 --> 00:45:04.800
Someone tried to make it work on a Raspberry Pi, and I was like, all right.

00:45:04.800 --> 00:45:12.919
I have seen people try to put it onto supercomputing clusters where it had no business being, and

00:45:12.919 --> 00:45:15.120
a lot of other really, really unique places.

00:45:15.120 --> 00:45:19.959
Did you see that Hacker News article about running a web server on a disposable vape?

00:45:19.959 --> 00:45:23.959
You know, I did see that article about running a web server on a disposable vape, and now

00:45:23.959 --> 00:45:30.040
I kind of want to put Positron on it.

00:45:30.040 --> 00:45:31.959
A quick question.

00:45:31.959 --> 00:45:37.879
Is tighter R integration on the roadmap, like detecting the R version from the R in block

00:45:37.879 --> 00:45:39.239
file?

00:45:39.239 --> 00:45:40.239
That's a good question.

00:45:40.239 --> 00:45:41.760
So the answer is yes.

00:45:41.760 --> 00:45:47.959
So we're continuing to innovate and develop Positron's R capabilities.

00:45:48.959 --> 00:45:51.760
I want you to remember the slide I shared a minute ago that had a picture of a screwdriver

00:45:51.760 --> 00:45:53.159
with a bunch of attachments on it.

00:45:53.159 --> 00:45:58.800
So the R support in Positron is like, it's a little attachment that goes into Positron.

00:45:58.800 --> 00:46:05.360
And so it is not yet as fully developed as RStudio is, and to be totally frank, it probably

00:46:05.360 --> 00:46:08.879
never will be.

00:46:08.879 --> 00:46:12.040
But we are making it better all the time.

00:46:12.040 --> 00:46:17.280
And yeah, better support for detecting the R version that you want to use automatically

00:46:17.600 --> 00:46:19.199
is definitely on the roadmap.

00:46:19.199 --> 00:46:23.080
I think from my perspective, one of the things that's most interesting about Positron is

00:46:23.080 --> 00:46:28.439
the things it's really good at are not the data science things, like the Git experience

00:46:28.439 --> 00:46:35.560
I think is better, like the find and file, find and replace in files, like where Positron

00:46:35.560 --> 00:46:40.040
can draw on this massive VS Code ecosystem rather than us having to create everything

00:46:40.040 --> 00:46:45.239
from scratch like in RStudio.

00:46:45.239 --> 00:46:49.399
What are some other languages that you see as kind of up and coming in data science?

00:46:49.399 --> 00:46:55.080
And are there anything on the roadmap for us at Posit in terms of supporting those things?

00:46:55.080 --> 00:46:57.600
That's a really good question.

00:46:57.600 --> 00:47:02.080
So there are a lot of languages that are really interesting for data science.

00:47:02.080 --> 00:47:07.439
Honestly, I think one of the most interesting languages for data science coming up right

00:47:07.439 --> 00:47:09.399
now is JavaScript.

00:47:09.399 --> 00:47:15.199
People who do it, it seems like a weird fit, but honestly, so did Python.

00:47:15.199 --> 00:47:18.439
So people are doing a lot of really interesting data science right now with literally just

00:47:18.439 --> 00:47:19.439
JavaScript.

00:47:19.439 --> 00:47:26.679
So, in fact, I've experimented a little bit with putting a JavaScript system into Positron

00:47:26.679 --> 00:47:28.959
so you can literally just write JavaScript code.

00:47:28.959 --> 00:47:32.760
Not actually available in any build, but I think that JavaScript as a language is very

00:47:32.760 --> 00:47:34.239
interesting for data science.

00:47:34.239 --> 00:47:38.040
And I like SQL, better SQL support on the roadmap too.

00:47:38.040 --> 00:47:42.919
Yes, SQL support is also very interesting to us and on our roadmap.

00:47:42.919 --> 00:47:48.600
The other thing, and don't stone me to death for this, that I think is kind of interesting

00:47:48.600 --> 00:47:51.800
possibly is like SAS support.

00:47:51.800 --> 00:47:54.600
Does anyone have a rock?

00:47:54.600 --> 00:48:00.919
I just think that's sort of really interesting that we're seeing a lot of companies want

00:48:00.919 --> 00:48:08.280
to move from SAS to other languages, but in some ways, VS Code and Positron and the alternative

00:48:08.280 --> 00:48:14.600
SAS engines like WPS and the language engine, there's sort of interesting ways of running

00:48:14.600 --> 00:48:21.239
that and very old code and very modern systems, which I just think that would be hilarious

00:48:21.239 --> 00:48:23.360
if we added that.

00:48:23.360 --> 00:48:28.600
That would be really funny, you're right.

00:48:28.600 --> 00:48:33.020
Does hiding complexity do a disservice to the user and ultimately create a dependence

00:48:33.060 --> 00:48:39.260
on the tool creator and lead to more towards more users who don't know what they want?

00:48:39.260 --> 00:48:40.260
That's a really good question.

00:48:40.260 --> 00:48:41.260
Who asked that?

00:48:41.260 --> 00:48:42.260
It's Scott.

00:48:42.260 --> 00:48:44.620
Scott, that's a great question.

00:48:44.620 --> 00:48:51.899
And so I think that this kind of requires a nuanced answer, and that is that it is true

00:48:51.899 --> 00:48:56.219
that it's not always the right call to hide complexity.

00:48:56.219 --> 00:49:01.419
And you kind of have to decide at what level of abstraction you want your tool to sit.

00:49:01.419 --> 00:49:06.540
And you also have to think about whether or not it's important for your user to understand

00:49:06.540 --> 00:49:08.100
what's happening.

00:49:08.100 --> 00:49:12.300
If you think about the tools that we have today for data science, really like the whole

00:49:12.300 --> 00:49:16.939
software stack, like really nobody understands the software stack, I think down all the way

00:49:16.939 --> 00:49:18.860
down to zero.

00:49:18.860 --> 00:49:23.979
At the end of the day, every tool is abstracting away some complexity from you.

00:49:23.979 --> 00:49:31.260
For example, if you use R, it's really not fair to say, well, are we really doing users

00:49:31.260 --> 00:49:35.780
a disservice by not showing them the raw assembly?

00:49:35.780 --> 00:49:36.780
Probably not, right?

00:49:36.780 --> 00:49:42.060
Like there's actually never a need for a user to know that, right?

00:49:42.060 --> 00:49:46.820
On the other hand, there are some places in RStudio, and I didn't have these in my slides,

00:49:46.820 --> 00:49:53.179
but for example, when you import data using RStudio, it actually doesn't just import it.

00:49:53.179 --> 00:49:57.899
What it does is it generates the code for you to run to do the import.

00:49:57.899 --> 00:50:00.100
It uses it to kind of teach you the code to write.

00:50:00.100 --> 00:50:05.459
So it is certainly true that you can create an artificial dependence that way.

00:50:05.459 --> 00:50:12.780
It is also true that you can use your tool to help teach people how to operate at a lower

00:50:12.780 --> 00:50:15.780
level of abstraction.

00:50:15.780 --> 00:50:22.379
But I would certainly also say that if you're going to abstract things away, you literally

00:50:22.379 --> 00:50:27.179
just need to ask yourself, is this something that the user needs to know, or is this something

00:50:27.179 --> 00:50:28.820
the user will never need to know?

00:50:28.899 --> 00:50:31.739
That's something you can only really know on a case-by-case basis.

00:50:31.739 --> 00:50:35.739
I think one of the framings that's been useful to me about thinking about this sometimes

00:50:35.739 --> 00:50:40.659
is like, do you get to worry about this, or do you have to worry about this?

00:50:40.659 --> 00:50:43.340
Like, yeah, case-by-case.

00:50:43.340 --> 00:50:48.540
So we're at 10 o'clock, so I'm sure if you've got other questions, please feel free to find

